# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: phase-locked-loop
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] A **charge pump** is a kind of DC-to-DC converter that uses capacitors for energetic charge storage to raise or lower voltage.
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] Charge-pump circuits are capable of high efficiencies, sometimes as high as 90–95%, while being electrically simple circuits.
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] Charge pumps use some form of switching device to control the connection of a supply voltage across a load through a capacitor in a two stage cycle.
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] In the first stage a capacitor is connected across the supply, charging it to that same voltage.
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] In the second stage the circuit is reconfigured so that the capacitor is in series with the supply and the load.
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] This doubles the voltage across the load - the sum of the original supply and the capacitor voltages.
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] The pulsing nature of the higher voltage switched output is often smoothed by the use of an output capacitor.
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] An external or secondary circuit drives the switching, typically at tens of kilohertz up to several megahertz.
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] The high frequency minimizes the amount of capacitance required, as less charge needs to be stored and dumped in a shorter cycle.
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] Charge pumps can double voltages, triple voltages, halve voltages, invert voltages, fractionally multiply or scale voltages (such as ×3⁄2, ×4⁄3, ×2⁄3, etc.) and generate arbitrary voltages by quickly alternating between modes, depending on the controller and circuit topology.
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] They are commonly used in low-power electronics (such as mobile phones) to raise and lower voltages for different parts of the circuitry - minimizing power consumption by controlling supply voltages carefully.
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] The term *charge pump* is also commonly used in phase-locked loop (PLL) circuits even though there is no pumping action involved unlike in the circuit discussed above.
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] A PLL charge pump is merely a bipolar switched current source.
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] This means that it can output positive and negative current pulses into the loop filter of the PLL.
[src:phase-locked-loop/charge-pump] It cannot produce higher or lower voltages than its power and ground supply levels.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] Phase-locked loop frequency synthesizers make use of frequency dividers to generate a frequency that is a multiple of a reference frequency.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] Frequency dividers can be implemented for both analog and digital applications.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] Analog frequency dividers are less common and used only at very high frequencies.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] Digital dividers implemented in modern IC technologies can work up to tens of GHz.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] A regenerative frequency divider, also known as a Miller frequency divider, mixes the input signal with the feedback signal from the mixer.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] This produces sum and difference frequencies $f_{in}/2$ , $3f_{in}/2$ at the output of the mixer.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] A low pass filter removes the higher frequency, and the $f_{in}/2$ frequency is amplified and fed back into the mixer.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] A free-running oscillator which has a small amount of a higher-frequency signal fed to it, will tend to oscillate in step with the input signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] Such frequency dividers were essential in the development of television.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] It operates similarly to an injection locked oscillator.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] In an injection-locked frequency divider, the frequency of the input signal is a multiple (or fraction) of the free-running frequency of the oscillator.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] While these frequency dividers tend to be lower power than broadband static (or flip-flop-based) frequency dividers, the drawback is their low locking range.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] The ILFD locking range is inversely proportional to the quality factor (Q) of the oscillator tank.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] In integrated circuit designs, this makes an ILFD sensitive to process variations.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] Care must be taken to ensure the tuning range of the driving circuit (for example, a voltage-controlled oscillator) must fall within the input locking range of the ILFD.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] For power-of-2 integer division, a simple binary counter can be used, clocked by the input signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] The least-significant output bit alternates at 1/2 the rate of the input clock, the next bit at 1/4 the rate, the third bit at 1/8 the rate, etc.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] An arrangement of flipflops is a classic method for integer-n division.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] Such division is frequency and phase coherent to the source over environmental variations, including temperature.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] The easiest configuration is a series where each flip-flop is a divide-by-2.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] For a series of three of these, such a system would be a divide-by-8.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] By adding additional logic gates to the chain of flip-flops, other division ratios can be obtained.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] Integrated circuit logic families can provide a single-chip solution for some common division ratios.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] Another popular circuit to divide a digital signal by an even integer multiple is a Johnson counter.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] This is a type of shift register network that is clocked by the input signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] The last register's complemented output is fed back to the first register's input.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] The output signal is derived from one or more of the register outputs.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] For example, a divide-by-6 divider can be constructed with a 3-register Johnson counter.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] This pattern repeats each time the input signal clocks the network.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] The output of each register is an f/6 square wave with 120° of phase shift between registers.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] Additional registers can be added to provide additional integer divisors.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] (*Classification:* *asynchronous sequential logic*) An arrangement of D flip-flops is a classic method for integer-n division.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] The easiest configuration is a series where each D flip-flop is a divide-by-2.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] More complicated configurations have been found that generate odd factors, such as a divide-by-5.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] Standard, classic logic chips that implement this or similar frequency division functions include the 7456, 7457, 74292, and 74294.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] A fractional-n frequency synthesizer can be constructed using two integer dividers, a divide-by-N, and a divide-by-(N + 1) frequency divider.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] With a modulus controller, N is toggled between the two values so that the VCO alternates between one locked frequency and the other.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] The VCO stabilizes at a frequency that is the time average of the two locked frequencies.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] By varying the percentage of time the frequency divider spends at the two divider values, the frequency of the locked VCO can be selected with very fine granularity.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] If the sequence of divide by N and divide by (N + 1) is periodic, spurious signals appear at the VCO output in addition to the desired frequency.
[src:phase-locked-loop/frequency-divider] Delta-sigma fractional-n dividers overcome this problem by randomizing the selection of N and (N + 1) while maintaining the time-averaged ratios.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Self-regulating mechanisms have existed since antiquity, and the idea of feedback started to enter economic theory in Britain by the 18th century, but it was not at that time recognized as a universal abstraction and so did not have a name.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The first ever known artificial feedback device was a float valve, for maintaining water at a constant level, invented in 270 BC in Alexandria, Egypt.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] This device illustrated the principle of feedback: a low water level opens the valve, the rising water then provides feedback into the system, closing the valve when the required level is reached.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] This then reoccurs in a circular fashion as the water level fluctuates.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Centrifugal governors were used to regulate the distance and pressure between millstones in windmills since the 17th century.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In 1788, James Watt designed his first centrifugal governor following a suggestion from his business partner Matthew Boulton, for use in the steam engines of their production.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Early steam engines employed a purely reciprocating motion, and were used for pumping water – an application that could tolerate variations in the working speed, but the use of steam engines for other applications called for more precise control of the speed.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In 1868, James Clerk Maxwell wrote a famous paper, "On governors", that is widely considered a classic in feedback control theory.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] This was a landmark paper on control theory and the mathematics of feedback.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] By the end of 1912, researchers using early electronic amplifiers (audions) had discovered that deliberately coupling part of the output signal back to the input circuit would boost the amplification (through regeneration), but would also cause the audion to howl or sing.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] This action of feeding back of the signal from output to input gave rise to the use of the term "feedback" as a distinct word by 1920.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Increasing the feedback produced superregeneration.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The development of cybernetics from the 1940s onwards was centred around the study of circular causal feedback mechanisms.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Over the years there has been some dispute as to the best definition of feedback.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] According to cybernetician Ashby (1956), mathematicians and theorists interested in the principles of feedback mechanisms prefer the definition of "circularity of action", which keeps the theory simple and consistent.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] For those with more practical aims, feedback should be a deliberate effect via some more tangible connection.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Focusing on uses in management theory, Ramaprasad (1983) defines feedback generally as "...information about the gap between the actual level and the reference level of a system parameter" that is used to "alter the gap in some way".
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] He emphasizes that the information by itself is not feedback unless translated into action.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Positive feedback: If the signal feedback from output is in phase with the input signal, the feedback is called positive feedback.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Negative feedback: If the signal feedback is out of phase by 180° with respect to the input signal, the feedback is called negative feedback.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] As an example of negative feedback, the diagram might represent a cruise control system in a car that matches a target speed, such as the speed limit.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The controlled system is the car; its input includes the combined torque from the engine and from the changing slope of the road (the disturbance).
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The car's speed (status) is measured by a speedometer.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The error signal is the difference between the speed as measured by the speedometer and the target speed (set point).
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The controller interprets the speed to adjust the accelerator, commanding the fuel flow to the engine (the effector).
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The resulting change in engine torque, the feedback, combines with the torque exerted by the change of road grade to reduce the error in speed, minimising the changing slope.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The terms "positive" and "negative" were first applied to feedback prior to WWII.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The idea of positive feedback already existed in the 1920s when the regenerative circuit was made.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Friis and Jensen (1924) described this circuit in a set of electronic amplifiers as a case where *the "feed-back" action is positive* in contrast to negative feed-back action, which they mentioned only in passing.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Harold Stephen Black's classic 1934 paper first details the use of negative feedback in electronic amplifiers.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Even before these terms were being used, James Clerk Maxwell had described their concept through several kinds of "component motions" associated with the centrifugal governors used in steam engines.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] He distinguished those that lead to a continued *increase* in a disturbance or the amplitude of a wave or oscillation, from those that lead to a *decrease* of the same quality.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The terms positive and negative feedback are defined in different ways within different disciplines.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] 2. the valence of the *action* or *effect* that alters the gap, based on whether it makes the recipient or observer *happy* (positive) or *unhappy* (negative).
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The two definitions may be confusing, like when an incentive (reward) is used to boost poor performance (narrow a gap).
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Referring to definition 1, some authors use alternative terms, replacing *positive* and *negative* with *self-reinforcing* and *self-correcting*, *reinforcing* and *balancing*, *discrepancy-enhancing* and *discrepancy-reducing* or *regenerative* and *degenerative* respectively.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] And for definition 2, some authors promote describing the action or effect as *positive* and *negative* *reinforcement* or *punishment* rather than feedback.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Yet even within a single discipline an example of feedback can be called either positive or negative, depending on how values are measured or referenced.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] This confusion may arise because feedback can be used to provide *information* or *motivate*, and often has both a *qualitative* and a *quantitative* component.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] While simple systems can sometimes be described as one or the other type, many systems with feedback loops cannot be shoehorned into either type, and this is especially true when multiple loops are present.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In general, feedback systems can have many signals fed back, and the feedback loops frequently contain mixtures of positive and negative feedback where positive and negative feedback can dominate at different frequencies or different points in the state space of a system.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The term bipolar feedback has been coined to refer to biological systems where positive and negative feedback systems can interact, the output of one affecting the input of another, and vice versa.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Some systems with feedback can have very complex behaviors, such as chaotic behaviors in non-linear systems, while others have much more predictable behaviors, such as those that are used to make and design digital systems.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Feedback is used extensively in digital systems.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] For example, binary counters and similar devices employ feedback where the current state and inputs are used to calculate a new state, which is then fed back and clocked back into the device to update it.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] By using feedback properties, the behavior of a system can be altered to meet the needs of an application; systems can be made stable, responsive or held constant.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] It is shown that dynamical systems with a feedback experience an adaptation to the edge of chaos.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Physical systems present feedback through the mutual interactions of their parts.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Feedback is also relevant for the regulation of experimental conditions, noise reduction, and signal control.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The thermodynamics of feedback-controlled systems has intrigued physicist since the Maxwell's demon, with recent advances on the consequences for entropy reduction and performance increase.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In biological systems such as organisms, ecosystems, or the biosphere, most parameters must stay under control within a narrow range around a certain optimal level under certain environmental conditions.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The deviation of the optimal value of the controlled parameter can result from changes in internal and external environments.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] A change of some of the environmental conditions may also require a change of that range for the system to function.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The value of the parameter to maintain is recorded by a reception system and conveyed to a regulation module via an information channel.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] An example of this is insulin oscillations.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Biological systems contain many types of regulatory circuits, both positive and negative.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] As in other contexts, *positive* and *negative* do not imply that the feedback causes *good* or *bad* effects.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] A negative feedback loop is one that tends to slow down a process, whereas a positive feedback loop tends to accelerate it.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The mirror neurons are part of a social feedback system, when an observed action is *mirrored* by the brain, like a self-performed action.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Normal tissue integrity is preserved by feedback interactions between diverse cell types mediated by adhesion molecules and secreted molecules that act as mediators; failure of key feedback mechanisms in cancer disrupts tissue function.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In an injured or infected tissue, inflammatory mediators elicit feedback responses in cells, which alter gene expression and change the groups of molecules expressed and secreted, including molecules that induce diverse cells to cooperate and restore tissue structure and function.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] This type of feedback is important because it enables coordination of immune responses and recovery from infections and injuries.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] During cancer, key elements of this feedback fail.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] This disrupts tissue function and immunity.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Mechanisms of feedback were first elucidated in bacteria, where a nutrient elicits changes in some of their metabolic functions.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Feedback is also central to the operations of genes and gene regulatory networks.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Repressor (see Lac repressor) and activator proteins are used to create genetic operons, which were identified by François Jacob and Jacques Monod in 1961 as *feedback loops*.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] These feedback loops may be positive (as in the case of the coupling between a sugar molecule and the proteins that import sugar into a bacterial cell), or negative (as is often the case in metabolic consumption).
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] On a larger scale, feedback can have a stabilizing effect on animal populations even when profoundly affected by external changes, although time lags in feedback response can give rise to predator-prey cycles.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In zymology, feedback serves as regulation of activity of an enzyme by its direct product(s) or downstream metabolite(s) in the metabolic pathway (see Allosteric regulation).
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal axis is largely controlled by positive and negative feedback, much of which is still unknown.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In psychology, the body receives a stimulus from the environment or internally that causes the release of hormones.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Release of hormones then may cause more of those hormones to be released, causing a positive feedback loop.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] This cycle is also found in certain behaviour.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] For example, "shame loops" occur in people who blush easily.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] When they realize that they are blushing, they become even more embarrassed, which leads to further blushing, and so on.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The climate system is characterized by strong positive and negative feedback loops between processes that affect the state of the atmosphere, ocean, and land.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] A simple example is the ice–albedo positive feedback loop whereby melting snow exposes more dark ground (of lower albedo), which in turn absorbs heat and causes more snow to melt.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Feedback is extensively used in control theory, using a variety of methods including state space (controls), full state feedback, and so forth.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In the context of control theory, "feedback" is traditionally assumed to specify "negative feedback".
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The most common general-purpose controller using a control-loop feedback mechanism is a proportional-integral-derivative (PID) controller.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Heuristically, the terms of a PID controller can be interpreted as corresponding to time: the proportional term depends on the *present* error, the integral term on the accumulation of *past* errors, and the derivative term is a prediction of *future* error, based on the current rate of change.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] For feedback in the educational context, see corrective feedback.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In ancient times, the float valve was used to regulate the flow of water in Greek and Roman water clocks; similar float valves are used to regulate fuel in a carburettor and also used to regulate tank water level in the flush toilet.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The Dutch inventor Cornelius Drebbel (1572–1633) built thermostats (c1620) to control the temperature of chicken incubators and chemical furnaces.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In 1745, the windmill was improved by blacksmith Edmund Lee, who added a fantail to keep the face of the windmill pointing into the wind.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In 1787, Tom Mead regulated the rotation speed of a windmill by using a centrifugal pendulum to adjust the distance between the bedstone and the runner stone (i.e., to adjust the load).
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The use of the centrifugal governor by James Watt in 1788 to regulate the speed of his steam engine was one factor leading to the Industrial Revolution.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Steam engines also use float valves and pressure release valves as mechanical regulation devices.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] A mathematical analysis of Watt's governor was done by James Clerk Maxwell in 1868.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The *Great Eastern* was one of the largest steamships of its time and employed a steam-powered rudder with a feedback mechanism designed in 1866 by John McFarlane Gray.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Joseph Farcot coined the word *servo* in 1873 to describe steam-powered steering systems.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Hydraulic servos were later used to position guns.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Elmer Ambrose Sperry of the Sperry Corporation designed the first autopilot in 1912.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Nicolas Minorsky published a theoretical analysis of automatic ship steering in 1922 and described the PID controller.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Internal combustion engines of the late 20th century employed mechanical feedback mechanisms such as the vacuum timing advance but mechanical feedback was replaced by electronic engine management systems once small, robust and powerful single-chip microcontrollers became affordable.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The use of feedback is widespread in the design of electronic components such as amplifiers, oscillators, and stateful logic circuit elements such as flip-flops and counters.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Electronic feedback systems are also very commonly used to control mechanical, thermal and other physical processes.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] If the signal is inverted on its way round the control loop, the system is said to have *negative feedback*; otherwise, the feedback is said to be *positive*.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Negative feedback is often deliberately introduced to increase the stability and accuracy of a system by correcting or reducing the influence of unwanted changes.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] This scheme can fail if the input changes faster than the system can respond to it.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] When this happens, the lag in arrival of the correcting signal can result in over-correction, causing the output to oscillate or "hunt".
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] While often an unwanted consequence of system behaviour, this effect is used deliberately in electronic oscillators.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Harry Nyquist at Bell Labs derived the Nyquist stability criterion for determining the stability of feedback systems.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] An easier method, but less general, is to use Bode plots developed by Hendrik Bode to determine the gain margin and phase margin.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Design to ensure stability often involves frequency compensation to control the location of the poles of the amplifier.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Electronic feedback loops are used to control the output of electronic devices, such as amplifiers.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] A feedback loop is created when all or some portion of the output is fed back to the input.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] A device is said to be operating *open loop* if no output feedback is being employed and *closed loop* if feedback is being used.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] When two or more amplifiers are cross-coupled using positive feedback, complex behaviors can be created.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Negative feedback occurs when the fed-back output signal has a relative phase of 180° with respect to the input signal (upside down).
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] This situation is sometimes referred to as being *out of phase*, but that term is also used to indicate other phase separations, as in "90° out of phase".
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Negative feedback can be used to correct output errors or to desensitize a system to unwanted fluctuations.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In feedback amplifiers, this correction is generally for waveform distortion reduction or to establish a specified gain level.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] A general expression for the gain of a negative feedback amplifier is the asymptotic gain model.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Positive feedback occurs when the fed-back signal is in phase with the input signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Under certain gain conditions, positive feedback reinforces the input signal to the point where the output of the device oscillates between its maximum and minimum possible states.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Positive feedback may also introduce hysteresis into a circuit.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] This can cause the circuit to ignore small signals and respond only to large ones.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] It is sometimes used to eliminate noise from a digital signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Under some circumstances, positive feedback may cause a device to latch, i.e., to reach a condition in which the output is locked to its maximum or minimum state.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] This fact is very widely used in digital electronics to make bistable circuits for volatile storage of information.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The loud squeals that sometimes occur in sound reinforcement, public address systems, and rock music are known as audio feedback.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] If a microphone is in front of a loudspeaker that it is connected to, the sound that the microphone picks up comes out of the speaker, and is picked up by the microphone and re-amplified.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] If the loop gain is sufficient, howling or squealing at the maximum power of the amplifier is possible.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The input signal is applied to the amplifier with open-loop gain *A* and amplified.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The output of the amplifier is applied to a feedback network with gain *B*, and subtracted from the input to the amplifier.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The loop gain is the product of all gains in the loop.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In the diagram shown, the loop gain is the product of the gains of the amplifier and the feedback network, *−AB*.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The minus sign is because the feedback signal is subtracted from the input.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The gains *A* and *B*, and therefore the loop gain, generally vary with the frequency of the input signal, and so are usually expressed as functions of the angular frequency *ω* in radians per second.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] It is often displayed as a graph with the horizontal axis frequency *ω* and the vertical axis gain.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In amplifiers, the loop gain is the difference between the open-loop gain curve and the closed-loop gain curve (actually, the 1/B curve) on a dB scale.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] An electronic oscillator is an electronic circuit that produces a periodic, oscillating electronic signal, often a sine wave or a square wave.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Oscillators convert direct current (DC) from a power supply to an alternating current signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] They are widely used in many electronic devices.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Common examples of signals generated by oscillators include signals broadcast by radio and television transmitters, clock signals that regulate computers and quartz clocks, and the sounds produced by electronic beepers and video games.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Oscillators designed to produce a high-power AC output from a DC supply are usually called inverters.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] There are two main types of electronic oscillator: the linear or harmonic oscillator and the nonlinear or relaxation oscillator.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] A latch or a flip-flop is a circuit that has two stable states and can be used to store state information.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] They typically constructed using feedback that crosses over between two arms of the circuit, to provide the circuit with a state.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] The circuit can be made to change state by signals applied to one or more control inputs and will have one or two outputs.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] It is the basic storage element in sequential logic.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Latches and flip-flops are fundamental building blocks of digital electronics systems used in computers, communications, and many other types of systems.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Latches and flip-flops are used as data storage elements.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Such data storage can be used for storage of *state*, and such a circuit is described as sequential logic.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] When used in a finite-state machine, the output and next state depend not only on its current input, but also on its current state (and hence, previous inputs).
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] It can also be used for counting of pulses, and for synchronizing variably-timed input signals to some reference timing signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Flip-flops can be either simple (transparent or opaque) or clocked (synchronous or edge-triggered).
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Although the term flip-flop has historically referred generically to both simple and clocked circuits, in modern usage it is common to reserve the term *flip-flop* exclusively for discussing clocked circuits; the simple ones are commonly called *latches*.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Using this terminology, a latch is level-sensitive, whereas a flip-flop is edge-sensitive.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] That is, when a latch is enabled, it becomes transparent, while a flip flop's output only changes on a single type (positive going or negative going) of clock edge.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Feedback loops provide generic mechanisms for controlling the running, maintenance, and evolution of software and computing systems.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Feedback loops are important models in the engineering of adaptive software, as they define the behaviour of the interactions among the control elements over the adaptation process, to guarantee system properties at run-time.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Feedback loops and foundations of control theory have been successfully applied to computing systems.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] In particular, they have been applied to the development of products such as IBM Db2 and IBM Tivoli.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] From a software perspective, the autonomic (MAPE, monitor analyze plan execute) loop proposed by researchers of IBM is another valuable contribution to the application of feedback loops to the control of dynamic properties and the design and evolution of autonomic software systems.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Feedback is also a useful design principle for designing user interfaces.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Video feedback is the video equivalent of acoustic feedback.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] It involves a loop between a video camera input and a video output, e.g., a television screen or monitor.
[src:phase-locked-loop/loop-gain] Aiming the camera at the display produces a complex video image based on the feedback.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] A **phase detector** or **phase comparator** is a frequency mixer, analog multiplier or logic circuit that generates a signal which represents the difference in phase between two signal inputs.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The phase detector is an essential element of the phase-locked loop (PLL).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Detecting phase difference is important in other applications, such as motor control, radar and telecommunication systems, servo mechanisms, and demodulators.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Phase detectors for phase-locked loop circuits may be classified in two types.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] A Type I detector is designed to be driven by analog signals or square-wave digital signals and produces an output pulse at the difference frequency.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The Type I detector always produces an output waveform, which must be filtered to control the phase-locked loop voltage-controlled oscillator (VCO).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] A type II detector is sensitive only to the relative timing of the edges of the input and reference pulses and produces a constant output proportional to phase difference when both signals are at the same frequency.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] This output will tend not to produce ripple in the control voltage of the VCO.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The phase detector needs to compute the phase difference of its two input signals.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Let α be the phase of the first input and β be the phase of the second.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The actual input signals to the phase detector, however, are not α and β, but rather sinusoids such as sin(α) and cos(β).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] In general, computing the phase difference would involve computing the arcsine and arccosine of each normalized input (to get an ever-increasing phase) and doing a subtraction.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Such an analog calculation is difficult.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Fortunately, the calculation can be simplified by using some approximations.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Assume that the phase differences will be small (much less than 1 radian, for example).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The expression suggests a quadrature phase detector can be made by summing the outputs of two multipliers.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The quadrature signals may be formed with phase shift networks.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Two common implementations for multipliers are the double balanced diode mixer, diode ring and the four-quadrant multiplier, Gilbert cell.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The first term provides the desired phase difference.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The second term is a sinusoid at twice the reference frequency, so it can be filtered out.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] In the case of general waveforms the phase detector output is described with the phase detector characteristic.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] A mixer-based detector (e.g., a Schottky diode-based double-balanced mixer) provides "the ultimate in phase noise floor performance" and "in system sensitivity." since it does not create finite pulse widths at the phase detector output.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Another advantage of a mixer-based PD is its relative simplicity.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Both the quadrature and simple multiplier phase detectors have an output that depends on the input amplitudes as well as the phase difference.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] In practice, the input amplitudes of input signals are normalized prior to input into the detector to remove the amplitude dependency.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] A phase detector suitable for square wave signals can be made from an exclusive-OR (XOR) logic gate.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] When the two signals being compared are completely in-phase, the XOR gate's output will have a constant level of zero.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] When the two signals differ in phase by 1°, the XOR gate's output will be high for 1/180th of each cycle — the fraction of a cycle during which the two signals differ in value.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] When the signals differ by 180° — that is, one signal is high when the other is low, and vice versa — the XOR gate's output remains high throughout each cycle.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] This phase detector requires inputs that are symmetrical square waves, or nearly so.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The XOR detector compares well to the analog mixer in that it locks near a 90° phase difference and has a pulse wave output at twice the reference frequency.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The output changes duty cycle in proportion to the phase difference.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Applying the XOR gate's output to a low-pass filter results in an analog voltage that is proportional to the phase difference between the two signals.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The remainder of its characteristics are very similar to the analog mixer for capture range, lock time, reference spurious and low-pass filter requirements.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Digital phase detectors can also be based on a sample and hold circuit, a charge pump, or a logic circuit consisting of flip-flops.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] When a phase detector based on logic gates is used in a PLL, it can quickly force the VCO to synchronize with an input signal, even when the frequency of the input signal differs substantially from the initial frequency of the VCO.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Such phase detectors also have other desirable properties, such as better accuracy when there are only small phase differences between the two signals being compared and superior pull-in range.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] A **phase frequency detector** (**PFD**) is an asynchronous circuit originally made of four flip-flops (i.e., the phase-frequency detectors found in both the RCA CD4046 and the motorola MC4344 ICs introduced in the 1970s).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The logic determines which of the two signals has a zero-crossing earlier or more often.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] When used in a PLL application, lock can be achieved even when it is off frequency.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The PFD improves the pull-in range and lock time over simpler phase detector designs such as multipliers or XOR gates.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Those designs work well when the two input phases are already near lock or in lock, but perform poorly when the phase difference is too large.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] When the phase difference is too large (which will happen when the instantaneous frequency difference is large), then the sign of the loop gain can reverse and start driving the VCO away from lock.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The PFD has the advantage of producing an output even when the two signals being compared differ not only in phase but in frequency.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] A phase frequency detector prevents a false lock condition in PLL applications, in which the PLL synchronizes with the wrong phase of the input signal or with the wrong frequency (e.g., a harmonic of the input signal).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] A *bang-bang* charge pump phase frequency detector supplies current pulses with fixed total charge, either positive or negative, to the capacitor acting as an integrator.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] A phase detector for a bang-bang charge pump must always have a **dead band** where the phases of inputs are close enough that the detector fires either both or neither of the charge pumps, for no total effect.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Bang-bang phase detectors are simple but are associated with significant minimum peak-to-peak jitter, because of drift within the dead band.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] In 1976 it was shown that by using a three-state phase frequency detector configuration (using only two flip-flops) instead of the original RCA/Motorola four flip-flops configurations, this problem could be elegantly overcome.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] For other types of phase-frequency detectors other, though possibly less-elegant, solutions exist to the dead zone phenomenon.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Other solutions are necessary since the three-state phase-frequency detector does not work for certain applications involving randomized signal degradation, which can be found on the inputs to some signal regeneration systems (e.g., clock recovery designs).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] A *proportional* phase detector employs a charge pump that supplies charge amounts in proportion to the phase error detected.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Specifically, some designs produce both up and down control pulses even when the phase difference is zero.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] These pulses are small, nominally the same duration, and cause the charge pump to produce equal-charge positive and negative current pulses when the phase is perfectly matched.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Phase detectors with this kind of control system don't exhibit a dead band and typically have lower minimum peak-to-peak jitter when used in PLLs.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] In PLL applications it is frequently required to know when the loop is out of lock.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] The more complex digital phase-frequency detectors usually have an output that allows a reliable indication of an out-of-lock condition.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] Some signal processing techniques such as those used in radar may require both the amplitude and the phase of a signal, to recover all the information encoded in that signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] One technique is to feed an amplitude-limited signal into one port of a product detector and a reference signal into the other port; the output of the detector will represent the phase difference between the signals.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] In optics phase detectors are also known as interferometers.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] For pulsed (amplitude modulated) light, it is said to measure the phase between the carriers.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] It is also possible to measure the delay between the envelopes of two short optical pulses by means of cross correlation in a nonlinear crystal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] And it is possible to measure the phase between the envelope and the carrier of an optical pulse, by sending a pulse into a nonlinear crystal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-detector] There the spectrum gets wider and at the edges the shape depends significantly on the phase.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] A **phase-locked loop** (**PLL**) is a control system that generates an output signal whose phase is fixed relative to the phase of an input signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Keeping the input and output phase in lockstep also implies a constant relationship between input and output frequencies.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] By incorporating a frequency divider, a PLL can generate a stable frequency that is a multiple of the input frequency.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] These properties are used for clock synchronization, demodulation, frequency synthesis, clock multipliers, and signal recovery from a noisy communication channel.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Since 1969, a single integrated circuit can provide a complete PLL building block, and nowadays has output frequencies from a fraction of a hertz up to many gigahertz.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] A simple analog PLL is an electronic circuit consisting of a variable frequency oscillator and a phase detector in a feedback loop (Figure 1).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The oscillator generates a periodic signal *Vo* with frequency proportional to an applied voltage, hence the term voltage-controlled oscillator (VCO).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The phase detector compares the phase of the VCO's output signal with the phase of periodic input reference signal *Vi* and outputs a voltage (stabilized by the filter) to adjust the oscillator's frequency to match the phase of *Vo* to the phase of *Vi*.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Phase can be proportional to time, so a phase difference can correspond to a time difference.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Left alone, different clocks will mark time at slightly different rates.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] A mechanical clock, for example, might be fast or slow by a few seconds per hour compared to a reference atomic clock (such as the NIST-F2).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] That time difference becomes substantial over time.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Instead, the owner can synchronize their mechanical clock (with varying degrees of accuracy) by phase-locking it to a reference clock.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] An inefficient synchronization method involves the owner resetting their clock to that more accurate clock's time every week.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] But, left alone, their clock will still continue to diverge from the reference clock at the same few seconds per hour rate.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] A more efficient synchronization method (analogous to the simple PLL in Figure 1) utilizes the fast-slow timing adjust control (analogous to how the VCO's frequency can be adjusted) available on some clocks.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Analogously to the phase comparator, the owner could notice their clock's misalignment and turn its timing adjustment a small proportional amount to make their clock's frequency a little slower (if their clock was fast) or faster (if their clock was slow).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] If they don't overcompensate, then their clock will be more accurate than before.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Over a series of such weekly adjustments, their clock's notion of a second would agree close enough with the reference clock, so they could be said to be locked both in frequency and phase.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] An early electromechanical version of a phase-locked loop was used in 1921 in the Shortt-Synchronome clock.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Spontaneous synchronization of weakly coupled pendulum clocks was noted by the Dutch physicist Christiaan Huygens as early as 1673.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Around the turn of the 19th century, Lord Rayleigh observed synchronization of weakly coupled organ pipes and tuning forks.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Vincent found that two electronic oscillators that had been tuned to oscillate at slightly different frequencies but that were coupled to a resonant circuit would soon oscillate at the same frequency.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Automatic synchronization of electronic oscillators was described in 1923 by Edward Victor Appleton.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In 1923, Harry Nyquist patented a PLL with a motor-generator as the oscillator.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In 1925, David Robertson, first professor of electrical engineering at the University of Bristol, introduced phase locking in his clock design to control the striking of the bell Great George in the new Wills Memorial Building.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Robertson's clock incorporated an electromechanical device that could vary the rate of oscillation of the pendulum, and derived correction signals from a circuit that compared the pendulum phase with that of an incoming telegraph pulse from Greenwich Observatory every morning at 10:00 GMT.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Including equivalents of every element of a modern electronic PLL, Robertson's system was notably ahead of its time in that its phase detector was a relay logic implementation of the transistor circuits for phase/frequency detectors not seen until the 1970s.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Robertson's work predated research towards what was later named the phase-lock loop in 1932, when British researchers developed an alternative to Edwin Armstrong's superheterodyne receiver, the Homodyne or direct-conversion receiver.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In the homodyne or synchrodyne system, a local oscillator was tuned to the desired input frequency and multiplied with the input signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The resulting output signal included the original modulation information.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The intent was to develop an alternative receiver circuit that required fewer tuned circuits than the superheterodyne receiver.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Since the local oscillator would rapidly drift in frequency, an automatic correction signal was applied to the oscillator, maintaining it in the same phase and frequency of the desired signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The technique was described in 1932, in a paper by Henri de Bellescize, in the French journal *L'Onde Électrique*.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In analog television receivers since at least the late 1930s, phase-locked-loop horizontal and vertical sweep circuits are locked to synchronization pulses in the broadcast signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In 1969, Signetics introduced a line of low-cost monolithic integrated circuits like the NE565 using bipolar transistors, which were complete phase-locked loop systems on a chip, and applications for the technique multiplied.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] A few years later, RCA introduced the CD4046 Micropower Phase-Locked Loop using CMOS, which also became a popular integrated circuit building block.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Phase-locked loop mechanisms may be implemented as either analog or digital circuits.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Both implementations use the same basic structure.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Some terms that are used are "analog phase-locked loop" (APLL), also referred to as a linear phase-locked loop" (LPLL), "digital phase-locked loop" (DPLL), "all digital phase-locked loop" (ADPLL), and "software phase-locked loop" (SPLL).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Phase detector, filter and oscillator are digital.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Phase detector is implemented by neuronal non-linearity, and the oscillator by rate-controlled oscillating neurons.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Functional blocks are implemented by software rather than specialized hardware.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] CP-PLL is a modification of phase-locked loops with a phase-frequency detector and square waveform signals.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Phase-locked loops are widely used for synchronization purposes; in space communications for coherent demodulation and threshold extension, bit synchronization, and symbol synchronization.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Phase-locked loops can also be used to demodulate frequency-modulated signals.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In radio transmitters, a PLL is used to synthesize new frequencies which are a multiple of a reference frequency, with the same stability as the reference frequency.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Some data streams, especially high-speed serial data streams (such as the raw stream of data from the magnetic head of a disk drive), are sent without an accompanying clock.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The receiver generates a clock from an approximate frequency reference, and then uses a PLL to phase-align it to the data stream's signal edges.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] This process is referred to as clock recovery.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] For this scheme to work, the data stream must have edges frequently enough to correct any drift in the PLL's oscillator.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Thus, a line code with a hard upper bound on the maximum time between edges (e.g.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] 8b/10b encoding) is typically used to encode the data.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] If a clock is sent in parallel with data, that clock can be used to sample the data.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Because the clock must be received and amplified before it can drive the flip-flops, which sample the data, there will be a finite, and process-, temperature-, and voltage-dependent delay between the detected clock edge and the received data window.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] This delay limits the frequency at which data can be sent.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] One way of eliminating this delay is to include a deskew PLL on the receive side, so that the clock at each data flip-flop is phase-matched to the received clock.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In that type of application, a special form of a PLL called a delay-locked loop (DLL) is frequently used.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Many electronic systems include processors of various sorts that operate at hundreds of megahertz to gigahertz, well above the practical frequencies of crystal oscillators.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Typically, the clocks supplied to these processors come from clock generator PLLs, which multiply a lower-frequency reference clock (usually 50 or 100 MHz) up to the operating frequency of the processor.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The multiplication factor can be quite large in cases where the operating frequency is multiple gigahertz and the reference crystal is just tens or hundreds of megahertz.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] All electronic systems emit some unwanted radio frequency energy.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Various regulatory agencies (such as the FCC in the United States) put limits on the emitted energy and any interference caused by it.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The emitted noise generally appears at sharp spectral peaks (usually at the operating frequency of the device and a few harmonics).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] A system designer can use a spread-spectrum PLL to reduce interference with high-Q receivers by spreading the energy over a larger portion of the spectrum.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Typically, the reference clock enters the chip and drives a PLL, which then drives the system's clock distribution.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The clock distribution is usually balanced so that the clock arrives at every endpoint simultaneously.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] One of those endpoints is the PLL's feedback input.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The function of the PLL is to compare the distributed clock to the incoming reference clock and vary the phase and frequency of its output until the reference and feedback clocks are phase and frequency matched.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] PLLs are ubiquitous—they tune clocks in systems several feet across, as well as clocks in small portions of individual chips.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Sometimes the reference clock may not actually be a pure clock at all, but rather a data stream with enough transitions that the PLL is able to recover a regular clock from that stream.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Sometimes the reference clock is the same frequency as the clock driven through the clock distribution, other times the distributed clock may be some rational multiple of the reference.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] A PLL may be used to synchronously demodulate amplitude-modulated (AM) signals.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The PLL recovers the phase and frequency of the incoming AM signal's carrier.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The recovered phase at the VCO differs from the carrier's by 90°, so it is shifted in phase to match and then fed to a multiplier.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The output of the multiplier contains both the sum and the difference frequency signals, and the demodulated output is obtained by low-pass filtering.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Since the PLL responds only to the carrier frequencies that are very close to the VCO output, a PLL AM detector exhibits a high degree of selectivity and noise immunity, which is not possible with conventional peak-type AM demodulators.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] However, the loop may lose lock where AM signals have 100% modulation depth.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] One desirable property of all PLLs is that the reference and feedback clock edges are brought into very close alignment.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The average difference in time between the phases of the two signals when the PLL has achieved lock is called the **static phase offset** (also called the **steady-state phase error**).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The variance between these phases is called **tracking jitter**.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Ideally, the static phase offset should be zero, and the tracking jitter should be as low as possible.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Phase noise is another type of jitter observed in PLLs, and is caused by the oscillator itself and by elements used in the oscillator's frequency control circuit.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Some technologies are known to perform better than others in this regard.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The best digital PLLs are constructed with emitter-coupled logic (ECL) elements, at the expense of high power consumption.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] To keep phase noise low in PLL circuits, it is best to avoid saturating logic families such as transistor-transistor logic (TTL) or CMOS.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Another desirable property of all PLLs is that the phase and frequency of the generated clock are unaffected by rapid changes in the voltages of the power and ground supply lines, as well as the voltage of the substrate on which the PLL circuits are fabricated.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] This is called substrate and supply noise rejection.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The higher the noise rejection, the better.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] To further improve the phase noise of the output, an injection locked oscillator can be employed following the VCO in the PLL.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In digital wireless communication systems (GSM, CDMA, etc.), PLLs are used to provide the local oscillator up-conversion during transmission and down-conversion during reception.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In most cellular handsets, this function has been largely integrated into a single integrated circuit to reduce the cost and size of the handset.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] However, due to the high performance required of base station terminals, the transmission and reception circuits are built with discrete components to achieve the levels of performance required.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] GSM local oscillator modules are typically built with a frequency synthesizer integrated circuit and discrete resonator VCOs.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Grid-tie inverters based on voltage source inverters source or sink real power into the AC electric grid as a function of the phase angle of the voltage they generate relative to the grid's voltage phase angle, which is measured using a PLL.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In photovoltaic applications, the more the sine wave produced leads the grid voltage wave, the more power is injected into the grid.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] For battery applications, the more the sine wave produced lags the grid voltage wave, the more the battery charges from the grid, and the more the sine wave produced leads the grid voltage wave, the more the battery discharges into the grid.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The block diagram shown in the figure shows an input signal, *F**I*, which is used to generate an output, *F**O*.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The input signal is often called the *reference signal* (also abbreviated *F**REF*).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] At the input, a phase detector (shown as the Phase frequency detector and Charge pump blocks in the figure) compares two input signals, producing an error signal which is proportional to their phase difference.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The error signal is then low-pass filtered and used to drive a VCO, which creates an output phase.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The output is fed through an optional divider back to the input of the system, producing a negative feedback loop.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] If the output phase drifts, the error signal will increase, driving the VCO phase in the opposite direction so as to reduce the error.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Thus, the output phase is locked to the phase of the input.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Analog phase-locked loops are generally built with an analog phase detector, low-pass filter and VCO placed in a negative feedback configuration.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] A digital phase-locked loop uses a digital phase detector; it may also have a divider in the feedback path or in the reference path, or both, in order to make the PLL's output signal frequency a rational multiple of the reference frequency.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] A non-integer multiple of the reference frequency can also be created by replacing the simple divide-by-*N* counter in the feedback path with a programmable pulse swallowing counter.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] This technique is usually referred to as a fractional-N synthesizer or fractional-N PLL.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The oscillator generates a periodic output signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Assume that initially the oscillator is at nearly the same frequency as the reference signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] If the phase from the oscillator falls behind that of the reference, the phase detector changes the control voltage of the oscillator so that it speeds up.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Likewise, if the phase creeps ahead of the reference, the phase detector changes the control voltage to slow down the oscillator.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Since initially the oscillator may be far from the reference frequency, practical phase detectors may also respond to frequency differences, so as to increase the lock-in range of allowable inputs.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Depending on the application, either the output of the controlled oscillator or the control signal to the oscillator, provides the useful output of the PLL system.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] A phase detector (PD) generates a voltage, which represents the phase difference between two signals.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In a PLL, the two inputs of the phase detector are the reference input and the feedback from the VCO.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The PD output voltage is used to control the VCO such that the phase difference between the two inputs is held constant, making it a negative feedback system.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Different types of phase detectors have different performance characteristics.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] For instance, the frequency mixer produces harmonics that add complexity in applications where spectral purity of the VCO signal is important.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The resulting unwanted (spurious) sidebands, also called "reference spurs" can dominate the filter requirements and reduce the capture range well below or increase the lock time beyond the requirements.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In these applications, the more complex digital phase detectors are used, which do not have as severe a reference spur component on their output.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Also, when in lock, the steady-state phase difference at the inputs using this type of phase detector is near 90 degrees.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In PLL applications, it is frequently required to know when the loop is out of lock.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] An XOR gate is often used for digital PLLs as an effective yet simple phase detector.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] It can also be used in an analog sense, with only slight modification to the circuitry.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The block commonly called the PLL loop filter (usually a low-pass filter) generally has two distinct functions.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The primary function is to determine loop dynamics, also called stability.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] This is how the loop responds to disturbances, such as changes in the reference frequency, changes of the feedback divider, or at startup.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Common considerations are the range over which the loop can achieve lock (pull-in range, lock range or capture range), how fast the loop achieves lock (lock time, lock-up time or settling time) and damping behavior.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Depending on the application, this may require one or more of the following: a simple proportion (gain or attenuation), an integral (low-pass filter) or derivative (high-pass filter).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Loop parameters commonly examined for this are the loop's gain margin and phase margin.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Common concepts in control theory, including the PID controller, are used to design this function.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The second common consideration is limiting the amount of reference frequency energy (ripple) appearing at the phase detector output that is then applied to the VCO control input.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] This frequency modulates the VCO and produces FM sidebands commonly called "reference spurs".
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The design of this block can be dominated by either of these considerations, or can be a complex process juggling the interactions of the two.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The typical trade-off of increasing the bandwidth is degraded stability.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Conversely, the tradeoff of extra damping for better stability is reduced speed and increased settling time.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Often, the phase noise is also affected.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] All phase-locked loops employ an oscillator element with variable frequency capability.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] This can be an analog VCO, either driven by analog circuitry in the case of an APLL or driven digitally through the use of a digital-to-analog converter as is the case for some DPLL designs.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Ring oscillators are commonly used in CMOS technology for low-area applications, whereas cross-coupled LC oscillators are preferred in low-phase noise applications.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Pure digital oscillators, such as a numerically controlled oscillator, are used in ADPLLs.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] PLLs may include a divider between the oscillator and the feedback input to the phase detector to produce a frequency synthesizer.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Some PLLs also include a divider between the reference clock and the reference input to the phase detector.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] If the divider in the feedback path divides by N and the reference input divider divides by M , it allows the PLL to multiply the reference frequency by $N/M$ .
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] It might seem simpler to just feed the PLL a lower frequency, but in some cases, the reference frequency may be constrained by other issues, and then the reference divider is useful.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Frequency multiplication can also be attained by locking the VCO output to the *N*th harmonic of the reference signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Instead of a simple phase detector, the design uses a harmonic mixer (sampling mixer).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The harmonic mixer turns the reference signal into an impulse train that is rich in harmonics.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The VCO output is coarse tuned to be close to one of those harmonics.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Consequently, the desired harmonic mixer output (representing the difference between the *N* harmonic and the VCO output) falls within the loop filter passband.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] It should also be noted that the feedback is not limited to a frequency divider.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] This element can be other elements, such as a frequency multiplier or a mixer.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The multiplier will make the VCO output a sub-multiple (rather than a multiple) of the reference frequency.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] A mixer can translate the VCO frequency by a fixed offset.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] For example, a divider following a mixer allows the divider to operate at a much lower frequency than the VCO without a loss in loop gain.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The equations governing a phase-locked loop with an analog multiplier as the phase detector and linear filter may be derived as follows.
