[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Phase-locked loops can also be analyzed as control systems by applying the Laplace transform.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The loop characteristics can be controlled by inserting different types of loop filters.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The simplest filter is a one-pole RC circuit.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] This is the form of a classic harmonic oscillator.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] where $\zeta$ is the damping factor and $\omega _{n}$ is the natural frequency of the loop.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The loop natural frequency is a measure of the response time of the loop, and the damping factor is a measure of the overshoot and ringing.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Ideally, the natural frequency should be high and the damping factor should be near 0.707 (critical damping).
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] With a single-pole filter, it is not possible to control the loop frequency and damping factor independently.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] A slightly more effective filter, the lag-lead filter includes one pole and one zero.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] This can be realized with two resistors and one capacitor.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Real world loop filter design can be much more complex, e.g., using higher-order filters to reduce various types or source of phase noise.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Digital phase-locked loops can be implemented in hardware, using integrated circuits such as a CMOS 4046.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] However, with microcontrollers becoming faster, it may make sense to implement a phase-locked loop in software for applications that do not require locking onto signals in the MHz range or faster, such as precisely controlling motor speeds.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Software implementation has several advantages, including easy customization of the feedback loop, including changing the multiplication or division ratio between the signal being tracked and the output oscillator.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Furthermore, a software implementation is useful to understand and experiment with.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The following example of a phase-locked loop implemented using a phase frequency detector is presented in MATLAB.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] This type of phase detector is robust and easy to implement.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In this example, an array `tracksig` is assumed to contain a reference signal to be tracked.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The oscillator is implemented by a counter, with the most significant bit of the counter indicating the on/off status of the oscillator.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] This code simulates the two D-type flip-flops that comprise a phase-frequency comparator.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] When either the reference or signal has a positive edge, the corresponding flip-flop switches high.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Once both reference and signal are high, both flip-flops are reset.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] Which flip-flop is high determines at that instant whether the reference or signal leads the other.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The error signal is the difference between these two flip-flop values.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] The pole-zero filter is implemented by adding the error signal and its derivative to the filtered error signal.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] This, in turn, is integrated to find the oscillator frequency.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] In practice, one would likely insert other operations into the feedback of this phase-locked loop.
[src:phase-locked-loop/phase-locked-loop] For example, if the phase-locked loop were to implement a frequency multiplier, the oscillator signal could be divided in frequency before it is compared to the reference signal.
